{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586071"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:25:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:25:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15054"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15054"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7742"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67578"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7742"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15054"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53030"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18908"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67578"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute interstitial nephritis is an inflammatory condition of the kidney tubules and interstitium that can lead to acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a feature of acute interstitial nephritis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urinalysis shows white blood cells and white blood cell casts","The classic triad includes fever, rash and basophilia","Lymphocytes are absent from the inflammatory infiltrate","Blood tests typically show thrombocytosis","Viral infections are the most common cause"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute interstitial nephritis (AIN) is characterised by inflammation of the renal interstitium and tubules. \u003Cstrong\u003EUrinalysis shows white blood cells and white blood cell casts\u003C/strong\u003E, along with eosinophils in the urine (\u003E1% of urinary white blood cells).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe classic triad includes fever, rash and basophilia\u003C/strong\u003E - The triad includes eosinophilia, not basophilia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphocytes are absent from the inflammatory infiltrate\u003C/strong\u003E - Lymphocytes and plasma cells are actually the predominant cell types\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood tests typically show thrombocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Thrombocytosis is not a typical feature of AIN\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral infections are the most common cause\u003C/strong\u003E - Drug reactions account for 75% of cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of AIN should be suspected in patients presenting with acute kidney injury, particularly if they have recently started new medications. The presence of fever, rash, and eosinophilia forms the classic triad, though this is not seen in all cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute interstitial nephritis classically presents with fever, rash, and eosinophilia","Urinalysis in acute interstitial nephritis shows white blood cells, white blood cell casts, and eosinophils","Drug reactions are the most common cause of acute interstitial nephritis, accounting for 75% of cases"],"references":["Caravaca-Font\u00e1n F, Fern\u00e1ndez-Ju\u00e1rez G, Praga M. Acute kidney injury in interstitial nephritis. Curr Opin Crit Care. 2019 Dec;25(6):558-564. doi: 10.1097/MCC.0000000000000654. PMID: 31503026.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53030"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15054"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53030"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:26:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:26:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7742"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67578"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":